Sure, here's an example of how to generate a table of contents automatically in a LaTeX document:

1. Add the `\tableofcontents` command where you want the table of contents to appear in your document. This command generates a list of the sections, subsections, and any other heading levels that you have used in your document.
2. Use the `\section`, `\subsection`, `\subsubsection`, and other heading commands to define the structure of your document. These commands automatically create entries in the table of contents.

Here's an example LaTeX document that demonstrates how to generate a table of contents:
```vbnet
\documentclass{article}

\usepackage{lipsum} % This package is for generating random text. You can remove it in your actual document.

\title{My LaTeX Document}
\author{John Doe}
\date{\today}

\begin{document}

\maketitle

\tableofcontents % This command generates the table of contents.

\section{Introduction}
\lipsum[1] % This generates random text for the introduction section.

\section{Methods}
\subsection{Experimental Setup}
\lipsum[2] % This generates random text for the experimental setup subsection.

\subsection{Data Analysis}
\lipsum[3] % This generates random text for the data analysis subsection.

\section{Results}
\lipsum[4] % This generates random text for the results section.

\section{Discussion}
\lipsum[5] % This generates random text for the discussion section.

\section{Conclusion}
\lipsum[6] % This generates random text for the conclusion section.

\end{document}
```
When you compile this document, LaTeX will automatically generate a table of contents based on the section and subsection headings that you have used. The table of contents will be placed at the location where you inserted the `\tableofcontents` command.

Note that the `\maketitle` command creates a title, author, and date section at the beginning of the document. The `\lipsum` command generates random text for the purposes of demonstration. You can replace it with your actual content.

Drawing a chessboard from a FEN notation in LaTeX can be quite involved, as LaTeX is primarily a typesetting system, not a graphics or programming language. However, it is possible with the help of some packages and a bit of manual work. Here's an example of how to do it:

1. First, make sure you have the following packages installed:

* `tikz`: for drawing the chessboard and pieces
* `xparse`: for defining new commands
* `pgf`: for general graphics operations

2. Next, define some commands to help draw the chessboard and pieces. Here's an example of what the code might look like:

```latex
\documentclass{article}
\usepackage{tikz,xparse,pgf}

% Define a command to draw the chessboard
\newcommand{\drawChessboard}[1]{
  \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.5]
    \foreach \x in {0,...,7} {
      \foreach \y in {0,...,7} {
        \pgfmathtruncatemacro{\label}{#1[\x+\y*8+1]}
        \ifodd\x\ifodd\y\else\fi\else\ifodd\y\else\fi\fi
        \node[draw,circle,inner sep=0.2cm,fill=gray] at (\x,\y) {\label};
      }
    }
  \end{tikzpicture}
}

% Define a command to draw a chess piece
\newcommand{\drawPiece}[2]{
  \begin{scope}[shift={(#1,#2)}]
    \fill[white] (-0.25,-0.25) rectangle (0.25,0.25);
    \pgfmathparse{#3 mod 2}
    \ifnum\pgfmathresult=0
      \fill[black] (-0.25,-0.25) rectangle (0.25,0.25);
    \fi
    \pgfmathparse{#3 / 2}
    \ifnum\pgfmathresult=0
      \fill[white] (-0.15,-0.15) rectangle (0.15,0.15);
    \else
      \fill[black] (-0.15,-0.15) rectangle (0.15,0.15);
    \fi
  \end{scope}
}

% Define a command to draw a chess piece at a given position on the board
\NewDocumentCommand{\drawChessPiece}{m m m}{
  \pgfmathtruncatemacro{\x}{#1}
  \pgfmathtruncatemacro{\y}{#2}
  \begin{scope}[shift={(\x,\y)}]
    \drawPiece{0}{0}{#3}
  \end{scope}
}

% Define a command to parse a FEN string and draw the corresponding chessboard
\NewDocumentCommand{\drawFEN}{m}{
  \pgfmathsetmacro{\boardSize}{int(8)}
  \pgfmathsetmacro{\rankSize}{int(8*\boardSize)}
  \xdef\FEN{#1}
  \foreach \rank [count=\i from 0] in {1,...,8} {
    \foreach \file [count=\j from 0] in {a,...,h} {
      \pgfmathtruncatemacro{\index}{\i*\rankSize+\j+1}
      \pgfmathtruncatemacro{\piece}{\FEN[\index-1]}
      \ifnum\piece>0
        \drawChessPiece{\j}{\i}{\piece}
      \fi
    }
  }
}
```

3. Finally, use the `\drawFEN` command to draw the chessboard from a FEN string. For example, the following code will draw the starting position of a chess game:

```latex
\begin{document}
\drawChessboard{rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1}
\end{document}
```

Note that this code is just an example, and you may need to modify it to suit your specific needs. Also, keep in mind that drawing chessboards and pieces in LaTeX can be quite slow and resource-intensive, especially for large boards or complex positions.

